; uploaded on {{dts|2009-07-03}}\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_43TO_OPj-8]\n|-\n| {{dts|2009-07-25}}\n| \"[[Dangerous (Michael Jackson song)|Dangerous]]\"\n| [[Michael Jackson]]\n| --\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ibsm_k8akyE]\n|-\n| {{dts|2009-08-29}}\n| \"[[Fire (2NE1 song)|Fire]]\"\n| [[2NE1]]\n| --\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NHEx4D8xoIM]\n|-\n| {{dts|November 4, 2009}}\n| Queen Medley\n| [[Queen (band)|Queen]]/[[Styx (band)|Styx]]\n| Songs included:\n* \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\"\n* \"[[We Will Rock You]]\"\n* \"[[Princes of the Universe]]\"\n* \"[[Another One Bites The Dust]]\"\n* \"[[I Want To Break Free]]\"\n* \"[[Breakthru (song)|Breakthru]]\"\n* \"[[Don't Stop Me Now]]\"\n* \"[[Mr Roboto]]\" by [[Styx (band)|Styx]]\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kRiUjXp_BOE]\n|-\n| {{dts|2009-11-28}}\n| \"[[Greased Lightning]]\"\n| ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''\n| includes {{Duration|m=6|s=40}} speech by Byron Garcia\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KACFo5V73ro]\n|-\n| {{dts|2010-01-23}}\n| \"[[They Don't Care About Us]]\"\n| Michael Jackson\n| featuring choreographer [[Travis Payne]] and \"MJ Dancers\" [[Daniel Celebre]] and [[Dres Reid]]\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mKtdTJP_GUI]\n|-\n| {{dts|2012-09-29}}\n| \"[[Gangnam Style]]\"\n| [[Psy (rapper)|PSY]]\n| --\n| [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o1AGTGLL_wg]\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== Criticism ==\n{{Criticism section|date=April 2018}}\nThe prison has been criticized by prison rehabilitation experts and [[human rights]] campaigners who claim that the enforced dance routines are exploitative and not proper rehabilitation. Some former prisoners have alleged violence against those who refuse to join in. [[Amnesty International]] notes that cruel, inhumane, and degrading conditions persist in Philippine prisons, jails, and other detention centres. They have stated their concerns about overcrowding, insufficient food provision, poor ventilation, and poor sanitation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8611740.stm?ls |title=Fast Track - What keeps Filipino prisoners dancing to Thriller? |publisher=BBC News |date=2010-04-09 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\nHuman rights group [[Karapatan]] has also filed complaints against the Garcias and the wardens, alleging inhuman treatment of detainees.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/icaught/story?id=3478161&page=1#.UHRIsXm9uSo |title=Prisoners' Dance: Celebration or Human Rights Violation? |date=2007-08-14 |last=Hunte |first=Tracie |work=ABC News |accessdate=2012-10-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207003857/http://abcnews.go.com/icaught/story?id=3478161&page=1#.UHRIsXm9uSo |archive-date=2009-12-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe CPDRC dancers have been featured in a number of news items.\n* Netflix created an original 5 part documentary by director Michele Josue called \"[[Happy Jail]]\" about the CPDRC and its consultant Marco Toral. The dancing inmates and their choreographer are featured prominently, as well as discussion about the benefits of the dancing program as to its rehabilitative value.\n*A thirty-minute documentary by SBS/Dateline and Journeyman Pictures entitled \"Jailhouse Rock\",<ref name=\"dateline\">{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wAjItY7X0Yc |title=Jailhouse Rock - Philippines |author=journeymanpictures |via=YouTube |date=2007-11-12 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref> a take on the popular [[Elvis Presley]] song takes a positive look at the program. Byron Garcia is quoted at the beginning saying humorously: \"This is what America has been longing for... a jailhouse rock, which they only saw in Elvis... Jailhouse... and they're rockin'.\"<ref name=\"dateline\" />\n* The British [[Channel 4]] Documentary ''Murderers on the Dancefloor'' broadcast in January 2008 portrayed life in the prison.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.quarkfilms.com/film/MURDERERS%20ON%20THE%20DANCEFLOOR |title=Murderers on the Dance Floor |work=Quark Films |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/3670231/Wednesdays-TV-and-radio-choices.html |title=Wednesday's TV & radio choices |date=2008-01-02 |author1=Catherine Gee |author2=Simon Horsford |author3=Patricia Wynn Davies |author4=Gillian Reynolds |work=The Telegraph |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref><!-- dead link: url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IiZu0y0xHBg --> The program showed various inmates praising Byron Garcia, the founder of the initiative\u2014many of whom had tattoos in recognition of Garcia. However, it also featured an anonymous ex-inmate who claimed Garcia employs certain prisoners to rough up with prisoners who refuse to dance.\n* Five housemates from the reality show ''[[Pinoy Big Brother: Celebrity Edition 2]]'' performed \"[[Rico Mambo]]\" with the inmates. The participants were: [[Victor Basa]], [[Megan Young]], [[Gaby Dela Merced]], [[Riza Santos]], and [[Mcoy Fundales]]. The CPDRC dancers had done the routine in an earlier video. The housemates received loud applause from the inmates after the dance number.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20071110-100053/Housemates_mambo__with__CPDRC_inmates |title=Housemates mambo with CPDRC inmates |last=Gallo |first=Nilda |work=Cebu Daily News - Inquirer Global Nation |date=2007-10-11 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130221172829/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20071110-100053/Housemates_mambo__with__CPDRC_inmates |archive-date=2013-02-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Responding to various criticism and persistent negative comments in the YouTube response section and alleged use of force to make the prisoners dance and using torture against dissenters who refused to take part, Byron Garcia who runs the prison and posts the videos put out a comment on the main page of CPDRC on YouTube refuting the allegations. He says in his message: \"There are sick people who think that dancing is a form of cruel punishment! Since when was dancing categorized as punishment? My fellow citizens of the world, cruel and violent forms of punishment are a thing of the past. If we make jails a living hell for the prisoners, then, we might just be sending out devils once they are released and re-integrated to society. To all \"non-believers\" of humane treatment of prisoners, and to all haters of our non-violent approach to rehabilitation, all I can say is ...get a life!\"{{qn|date=October 2012|reason=need specific part of byron's youtube channel quoting this}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/byronfgarcia |title=byronfgarcia's channel |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref><!-- Byron F. Garcia's message after the criticism of the program. -->\n* CPDRC followed that up by putting a bilingual song in the local language and in English explaining the program. The video release called ''CPDRC Song'' included lyrics that say: \"We're the dancing inmates of CPDRC, we dance and entertain the world and make you all happy, a new approach to rehabilitation, representing Cebu province and the rest of our nation. We're the dancing inmates of CPDRC, fun and laughter, smiles in every corner. Got the world's attention, coz we've got moves, and now all millions of you say you've watched us on YouTube, CPDRC, CPDRC, CPDRC Inmates\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x-hinTjCD64 |title=CPDRC Song |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref><!-- The CPDRC Song explaining the notion behind the CPDRC Dancing Inmates program -->\n* The ''Thriller'' video also inspired a short documentary by young filmmaker [[Pepe Diokno (director)|Pepe Diokno]], entitled ''Dancing for Discipline''. The documentary is a pointed examination of the cultures of power in Philippine systems, with telling interviews of Byron Garcia and inmates Wenjiel Resane and Crisanto Niere. In a column for the [[Philippine Star]] Diokno writes, \"Jails are a microcosm of society, and in them we can clearly see how the cultures of power and patronage play. This is what ''Dancing for Discipline'' is about.\"<ref>[http://www.philstar.com/archives.php?aid=20071130109&type=2 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315221025/http://www.philstar.com/archives.php?aid=20071130109&type=2 |date=March 15, 2008 }}</ref><!-- Notes from the field:Dancing for Discipline --> The film was funded from a [[Grant (money)|grant]] by [[USAID]] through the [[Asia Foundation]], and is part of a series of [[short films]] about [[Philippine]] [[jails]], entitled ''Rock the Rehas''. The three other films in the series are ''DokumenTADO: Rock the Rehas'' by Tado Jimenez, ''Buhay Looban'' by [[Lourd de Veyra]], and ''1048:2261'' by [[Gang Badoy]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view_article.php?article_id=85220 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927122906/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/lifestyle/lifestyle/view_article.php?article_id=85220 |archive-date=2008-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><!-- Inquirer.net, Prison break --> These premiered on November 25, 2007, in [[Makati]], [[Philippines]], with [[Philippine Supreme Court]] Justice [[Reynato Puno]] in attendance, hailing the effort.\n* The Korean Sun Dance Troupe danced before the inmates for [[Valentine's Day]] 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20080214-118804/Koreans-to-join-inmates-V-Day-dance |title=Koreans to join inmates' V-Day dance |work=Cebu Daily News - Inquirer Global Nation |date=2008-02-14 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |last=Gallo |first=Nilda |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218030203/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20080214-118804/Koreans-to-join-inmates-V-Day-dance |archive-date=2008-02-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* The Film [[Samsara (2011 film)|Samsara]] has a sequence featuring CPDRC dancers.\n* The Japanese [[transgender]] artist / comedian [[Ai Haruna]] visited the prison and performed some of her acts. She also filmed the event to be shown on Japanese television.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gs3owwEARFw |title=Ai Haruna |author=byronfgarcia |via=YouTube |date=2009-03-16 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n* [[Los del R\u00edo]] sent a message of support saying that in their remake of their popular hit [[Macarena (song)|Macarena]] produced by [[Jon Secada]], they will include featured footage from the CPDRC prisoners dance routine of the song.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c_WVmoRCWpo |title=\"Macarena\" (Jon Secada Remix) with live presentation |author=byronfgarcia |via=YouTube|date=2008-07-27 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n* Drag queen Alvin performed in front of the CPDRC inmates cross-dressed as a nurse on the occasion of Byron Garcia's birthday.<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HcNWJqyGNa0 |title=CPDRC Guest Talents (ALVIN)! |author=byronfgarcia |via=YouTube |date=16 July 2009 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n* CNN's [[Joy Behar]] interviewed [[Travis Payne]], the Michael Jackson choreographer on the ''[[Joy Behar Show]]'' about the CPDRC prison program and his experiences preparing \"They Don't Know About Us\" dance routine with the inmates.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Behar |first=Joy |authorlink=Joy Behar |date=2010-01-25 |title=New hit for Filipino prison |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/bestoftv/2010/01/25/jb.prison.video.cnn |publisher=CNN.com |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n* CPDRC Dancing Inmates were offered to appear in a [[Procter & Gamble]] advertisement for detergent products. But Cebu Governor [[Gwendolyn Garcia]], who also serves as Cebu provincial jailer, turned down the P250,000 offer. \"The dancing inmates should not be used for commercial purposes to preserve the nobility of this world phenomenon\u201d, Governor Garcia said.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/242880/capitol-turns-down-ad-offer-dancing-inmates |title=Capitol turns down ad offer for dancing inmates |work=The Manila Bulletin |date=2010-02-10 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |last=Mosqueda Jr. |first=Mars}}</ref>\n* In 2011, the popular ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' series broadcast on the American [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network made direct reference to the Dancing Inmates. In one particular ''Glee'' episode, known as the \"Super Bowl\" episode in 2011, the instructor [[Will Schuester]] (played by [[Matthew Morrison]]) is shown speaking passionately to his arts students saying: \"Remember a few years ago when that Philippines prison performed that mega performance of \"Thriller\" and put it on [[YouTube]]? It took them 4 months to rehearse that number. Prisoner-on-prisoner crime dropped... 80%. Doing that together as a team created a unity within that prison. And that's what I am looking to do it here.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mb.com.ph/articles/303351/pinoy-dancing-inmates-inspire-glee-number |title=Pinoy dancing inmates inspire ''Glee'' number |work=Manilla Bulletin |date=2011-02-09 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |last=Villagomez |first=Kaye }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===''Prison Dancer: The Musical''===\nThe Dancing Inmates inspired the launch of a stage musical entitled ''Prison Dancer: The Musical''. The musical play was staged in [[New York City|New York]] during the New York Music Festival (NYMF) in July 2012 at the St. Clements Theatre. The story revolves around the lives of eight Filipino maximum-security prisoners who get a shot at changing their lives when a video of their dance-based rehabilitation program becomes a YouTube hit. The main character, Christian Escodero was played by Filipino-American actor [[Jose Llana]]. The play was created by writer-director-composer Romeo Candido and writer Carmen De Jesus, who met while performing in the musical [[Miss Saigon]].<ref name=inquirer>{{Cite web |title=Cebu's dancing inmates inspire New York musical |work=Cebu Daily News |date=2012-06-22 |last=Matus |first=Carmel Loise}}</ref>\n\n===''Prison Dancer: The Interactive Web Musical''===\nIn 2012, [[Filipino Canadian]] singer-actor [[Mikey Bustos]] starred in a 12-episode interactive web series titled ''Prison Dancer: The Interactive Web Musical'' inspired mainly by the CPDRC dancers.<ref name=fb>[https://www.facebook.com/prisondancer Facebook: ''Prison Dancer'' page]</ref> The series also featured 12 original songs with music and lyrics by Romeo Candido and script by Romeo Candido and Carmen De Jesus, a creative team who met while performing in [[Miss Saigon]]. The series recounts the story of six Filipino prisoners whose lives are forever changed when they decide to form a dancing group inside the prison and turn a maximum security jailhouse into a world stage. This web series is an adaptation of Candido and De Jesus' stage musical production, Prison Dancer: The Musical.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://orangemagazinetv.com/2012/prison-dancer-the-interactive-web-musical-mikey-bustos/ |title=Get ready for ''Prison Dancer: The Interactive Web Musical'' this coming March 2012 |work=Orange Magazine TV |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |last=Villanueva |first=Jeman |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204203034/http://orangemagazinetv.com/2012/prison-dancer-the-interactive-web-musical-mikey-bustos/ |archive-date=2012-12-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The episodes were titled chronologically \"Point of View\", \"Day One\", On the Inside\", \"Lose Your Way\", \"Pak Yow\", \"Evermore\", \"Step\", \"Loveteams\", \"This Great Divide\", \"Breakout\", \"Finally Free\" and Sensation\".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL7CB916433DDAFF9A&feature=plcp YouTube channel for ''Prison Dancer'']</ref>\n\n===''Dance of the Steel Bars''===\nIn 2013, a film, ''Dance of the Steel Bars'' was launched through Portfolio Films International. The 94-minute action and adventure drama film that premiered in the Philippines on June 12, 2013 and is greatly inspired by the CPDRC Dancing Inmates of Cebu. Upon insistence of the directors, the film's first screening was held inside the Cebu Provincial Detention and Rehabilitation Center a week earlier on June 7.<ref name=\"danceofthesteelbars.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.danceofthesteelbars.com/|title=Dance Of The Steelbars - Portfolio Films In Philippines Cinemas Nationwide Summer 2013|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029183228/http://www.danceofthesteelbars.com/|archive-date=29 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=mst>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/312756/showbiz/from-youtube-to-dance-of-the-steel-bars-filipino-prisoners-prance-to-fame#sthash.eoUFVooc.dpuf |title=From YouTube to 'Dance of the Steel Bars,' Filipino prisoners prance to fame |work=GMA Network |date=2013-06-13 |accessdate=2016-03-22 |last=Cabrera |first=Michaela}}</ref> Jointly directed by Cesar Apolinario, a GMA News and Public Affairs reporter and host and Marnie Manicad, producer-director of National Geographic documentaries, it stars Dingdong Dantes and Patrick Bergin. The screenwriters were Cris Lim and Michael Villar. The film tells the story of Frank Parish (played by Bergin), a retired US fireman and philanthropist who finds himself wrongly accused of murder of a local Filipino. Stuck in a Philippines prison, Frank becomes friends with an imprisoned dance instructor Mando (played by Dingdong Dantes) convicted of killing a transsexual. whose passion for dancing will topple the corrupt system that weighs down the inmates' chance to become better individuals. Allona, a transvestite (played by Joey Paras) in the Cebu Provincial Detention and Rehabilitation Center plays role of a dance instructor who tries to contribute to prison reforms by teaching his fellow inmates dance exercises. Also in the film are Ricky Davao, the jail warden, Gabe Mercado, as Diaz, the corrupt and ambitious deputy warden and Thou Reyes, as Dong Mata, a criminally insane hatchet man of the deputy warden. It was filmed on location in Cebu and Manila and some scenes actually filmed inside Cebu prison filmed many inmates in various roles. Cebu Governor Gwen Garcia played a cameo as herself. Cindera Che, a well-known performance coach based in Los Angeles, choreographed the dance performances in the movie. Edward White, a London-based composer, wrote the score for the movie.<ref name=\"danceofthesteelbars.com\"/><ref name=manilastandard>{{Cite web |url=http://manilastandardtoday.com/showbitz/simply-red-by-isah-v-red/105335/a-film-we-can-all-be-proud-of.html |title=A film we can all be proud of |work=Manila Standard Today |date=2013-06-13 |accessdate=2016-03-22 |last=Red |first=Isah V.}}</ref> the film received 4 nominations for the [[32nd Luna Awards]].\n\n== Implementation in other prisons ==\nByron Garcia, the warden who created the dancing program for the inmates, has put up a team of former \"Dancing Inmates\" to spread the message of \"Music and Dance Therapy\" to all jails nationwide in the Philippines. This is a pioneering initiative to institutionalize music therapy in other jails, similar to CPDRC's original program, with Cebu former inmates dancing making a tour of three prisons initially, Manila City Jail, Makati City Jail, and Quezon City Jail according to an agreement signed between Resendo M. Dial, chief of Philippines \"Bureau of Jail Management and Penology\" (BJMP) and Byron Garcia on March 26, 2010 as a collaborative effort to introduce music therapy in jail facilities nationwide.\n\nOn the occasion of the signing of the protocol, Garcia characterized general prison facilities as \"living hells\", because those who are in penology and rehabilitation \"are missing out the essence of compassion, redemption and restoration in jail management\". He added: \"They are too busy looking for creative ways to punish an offender instead of restoring him to become the human being that he is. We have to look at prisons beyond the cycle of crime and punishment and certainly look inside underlying social, cultural and scriptural implications of rehabilitation. As it is, those creative ways of punishing offenders that have led to restrictive and punitive conditions in jails have also bred demons out of prisoners\". Garcia said that this therapeutic protocol of dance and music is meant to restore dignity to people who suffer the stigma of incarceration and restore self-esteem to inmates because they are alienated from society. Therapeutic music and dance is meant to help prisoners cope with their depression and anxiety, improve their well-being as they go through a transition phase and reintegrate to society. Music is a protocol to heal them of emotional and psychological disorders and trauma as a result of the offense or incarceration\". He concluded that \"the experience of the CPDRC Dancing Inmates has proven a clinical breakthrough of using therapeutic music and dance in healing, restoring and rehabilitating inmates to become dignified human beings. This is actually what prompted BMJP to take interest in spreading such a program\", he said.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/byronfgarcia|title=byronfgarcia|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nA group of former dancing inmates will also tour the country's prisons for presentations in addition to a series of public performances to increase awareness to the program among the general population.\n\nThe offshoots of the program can be seen in The Quezon City Dancing Inmates and the Manila City Jail Dancing Inmates programs, greatly structured on the concepts applied in CPDRC.\n\n== Awards ==\nIn April 2011, during the 10th [[Tribeca Film Festival]], Byron Garcia was awarded Tribeca's \"[[Disruptive Innovator Award]] 2011\", the second annual award of the sort.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://radiantview.com/blog/2011/05/02/byron-garcia-is-honored-at-the-2nd-annual-disruptive-innovation-award-at-the-tribeca-film-festival/ |accessdate=May 29, 2011}}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><!-- Lorna L. Dietz article in ''Radiant View'': Byron Garcia: Honoree, Second Annual Disruptive Innovation Awards at Tribeca Film Festival -->\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|u=byronfgarcia|Byron F. Garcia}}\n* {{Youtube|hMnk7lh9M3o|\"Thriller\" (original upload)}}\n* {{Youtube|wAjItY7X0Yc|Jailhouse Rock documentary}}\n* {{Youtube|tfh7tpd895I|Journeyman Pictures documentary}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/prisondancer/ Prison Dancer: The Musical]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/prisondancer/ Prison Dancer: The Interactive Webmusical]\n\n{{coord missing|Philippines}}\n\n{{Corrections in the Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cpdrc dancers}}\n[[Category:Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Culture in Cebu City]]\n", "text_old": "'''CPDRC Dancing Inmates''' or the '''CPDRC dancers''' is a collective of [[Prisoner|prison inmates]] in [[Cebu Provincial Detention and Rehabilitation Center]] (CPDRC), a maximum security prison in [[Cebu City|Cebu]], in [[Cebu|Cebu Province]], [[Philippines]] where the prisoners perform dance routines as part of their daily exercise and rehabilitation, and many of their performances are filmed and released online, making them a popular feature among fans and veritable [[Internet celebrity|online celebrities]].\n\nByron F. Garcia, the official security advisor to the Cebu government, is credited for starting a program of choreographed exercise routines for the inmates. He was appointed head of the prison by his sister [[Gwendolyn Garcia]], then governor of Cebu. In 2006, he began uploading videos of the dance performances; its best known video was the [[Thriller (viral video)|rendition]] of [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Thriller (Michael Jackson song)|Thriller]]\" video, uploaded in 2007. Other music video performances covering popular songs were also uploaded, and public performances were held through 2010, including some outside the facility. The dance program was launched at other prison facilities, has been referenced by other television shows worldwide, and inspired the creation of several documentaries, musicals and drama films.\n\n== History ==\nByron Garcia had originally wanted to introduce a program at Cebu Provincial Detention and Rehabilitation Center (CPDRC) where inmates would exercise for an hour each day.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=12643181 |title=Filipino Inmates' Video Is a 'Thriller' on the Web |publisher=NPR |agency=Associated Press |date=2007-08-09 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref> He also claims in a British [[documentary]] that his inspiration came while watching the movie ''[[The Shawshank Redemption]]'' in particular the scene where the sounds of [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s ''[[The Marriage of Figaro|Figaro]]'' flood the prison yard.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}} Garcia initially introduced an exercise program where the prisoners marched in unison, starting out with marching to the beat of a drum, but moved on to [[Dance|dancing]] to [[pop music]]; he began with one of his favourite songs, [[Pink Floyd]]'s \"[[Another Brick in the Wall]]\".<ref name=\"npr\"/> He chose camp music such as \"[[In the Navy]]\" and \"[[Y.M.C.A. (song)|Y.M.C.A.]]\" by the [[Village People]], so macho prisoners would not be offended at being asked to dance.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\nGarcia's first upload of prisoner choreography was the [[Algorithm March]], with 967 inmates,<ref>{{cite AV media |author=byronfgarcia |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WjMd2Vabcv8 |title=Algorithm March with Prisoners |via=YouTube |date=2006-10-01 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref> but only generated 400 views in its first eight months.<ref name=\"npr\"/> The next upload, ''Thriller'', however, enjoyed a massive response.\n\nThe prison now even has its own official [[choreographer]] teachers, like Vince Rosales and Gwen Laydor. Some prisoners are chosen more prominently for more sophisticated routines while the general prison population (sometimes up to 1,500 inmates) participate with simpler more accessible routines.\n\n=== ''Thriller'' video ===\n{{Main|Thriller (viral video)}}\nOn July 17, 2007, Garcia uploaded \"Thriller\" on [[YouTube]],<ref name=\"thriller\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hMnk7lh9M3o |title=\"Thriller\" (original upload) |author=byronfgarcia |via=YouTube |date=2007-07-17 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref> a rendition of [[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Michael Jackson's music video]].<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6917318.stm |title=Philippine jailhouse rocks to Thriller |date=2007-07-26 |work=BBC News |accessdate=2007-08-17}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite web |last=MacKinnon |first=Ian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/international/story/0,,2136222,00.html |title=Jailhouse rocks: Philippine inmates' Thriller routine an internet hit |work=The Guardian |publisher=The Guardian News Limited |date=2007-07-27 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite video |url=https://www.reuters.com/video/2007/08/01/jail-house-rockers-are-big-hit?videoId=62432 |title=Jail house rockers are big hit (2:15) |date=2007-08-01 |publisher=Reuters.com}}</ref> The video has Crisanto Nierre as Michael Jackson's role and openly gay inmate Wenjiel Resane as the role of Jackson's girlfriend.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Paul |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/topstories/2007-08-09-2069158024_x.htm |title=Inmate 'Thriller' video is Web hit |agency=Associated Press |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=Gannett Co. |date=2007-08-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CSp3a6mT960 |title=Philippine Inmates Dance Again |author=kenkenproductions |via=YouTube |date=2007-09-10 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref> Both Crisanto Nierre and Wenjiel Resane enjoy popularity amongst YouTube fans, and their faces usually highlighted quite often in most later videos.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012|reason=need article to support highlighting the two inmates}}{{tone inline|date=October 2012|reason=popularity}}\n\nOn December 19, in an article on \"Most Popular Viral Videos\", ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine ranked CPDRC's \"Thriller\" fifth on its Top 10 list. ''Time'''s stated description of the prisoners was: \"Orange-jumpsuited accused murderers, rapists, and drug dealers paid homage to Michael Jackson's Thriller in a dance performance filmed at the Cebu Provincial Detention and Rehabilitation Center in the Philippines\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/73615/Cebu-dancing-inmates-video-makes-Time-list |title=Cebu dancing inmates video makes Time list |work=GMA News.tv |publisher=GMA Network |date=2007-12-20 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Public performances ===\nOn October 6, 2007, Cardinal Archbishop [[Ricardo Vidal]] visited CPDRC for the first time, and the prisoners performed six dances for him, as part of the celebration of the Prison Awareness Month; the Archbishop noted, \"It was a marvelous show of discipline. If only they had practiced that (discipline) in their lives, they wouldn't be here.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/ceb/2007/10/07/news/cardinal.urges.know.more.than.inmates.dances.html |title=Cardinal Urges Know More Than Inmates Dances |date=2007-10-07 |work=Sun.Star |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811000734/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/ceb/2007/10/07/news/cardinal.urges.know.more.than.inmates.dances.html |archivedate=August 11, 2009 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\nCPDRC requested to participate in the 438th Founder's Day celebration. About 20 inmates were chosen to perform in front of the Cebu Capitol. They performed a medley of \"Thriller\", \"[[Jump (Van Halen song)|Jump]]\", and \"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\". Donations from the performance totaled 1.6 million peso ({{US$|35,000}}).<ref name=\"npr\"/> The governor and provincial officials were so moved, that they included all 1,500 inmates in a share of the mid-year bonuses for Capitol employees. Each inmate was given 1,000 Philippines pesos ({{US$|22}}) for good behavior.<ref name=\"npr\"/><ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ehpyrheu450 |title=At the Cebu Capitol |author=byronfgarcia |via=YouTube |date=2007-08-08 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref><!-- this citation only supported July 2007 youtube 9 million hits\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/75067/2007-The-year-Pinoys-became-YouTube-darlings |title=2007: The year Pinoys became YouTube darlings |work=GMA News Online |last=Tumbocon Jr. |first=Mauro Feria |date=2008-01-03 |accessdate=2012-10-07}}</ref> --> On December 27, Michael Rama, acting mayor of [[Cebu City]], announced that the Sinulog Foundation executive director Ricky Ballesteros informed the former of the possibility of CPDRC\u2019s participation, but was concerned about parade security.<ref>See:\n* {{cite news |url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/74286/Cebu-mulls-Thriller-inmates-participation-in-Sinulog |title=Cebu mulls 'Thriller' inmates in Sinulog |date=2007-12-27 |agency=Sun.Star |work=GMA News.tv |accessdate=2012-10-08 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/ceb/2007/12/27/news/inmates.dance.area.limited.html |title=Inmates' dance area limited |publisher=Sun.Star |date=2007-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926183108/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/ceb/2007/12/27/news/inmates.dance.area.limited.html |archivedate=September 26, 2008 }}</ref> In January 2008, Cebu provincial governor [[Gwendolyn Garcia|Gwen Garcia]], visited CPDRC and took part in some of the dancing exercises with the prisoners.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Waaq8cb39Q |title=Mabuhi |author=byronfgarcia |via=YouTube |date=2008-01-22 |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref><ref name=\"torrecampo\"/><!-- Governor Gwen Garcia dancing with the Dancing Inmates -->\n\n\"[[Together in Electric Dreams]]\" by [[Philip Oakey]] and [[Giorgio Moroder]], and \"[[Ice Ice Baby]]\" by [[Vanilla Ice]] were presented during the Garcia's visit to the prison, on her birthday in October.{{When|date=October 2012|reason=what year did this happen? was it a second visit? only have youtube video showing January 2008 performance}}{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}} A competition was held amongst the prisoners as to who would take the lead role of Vanilla Ice in the dance.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nIn April 2008, CPDRC established a two-hour program, planned for the last Saturday of every month, where visitors could watch the inmates perform, have their pictures taken with inmates, and buy souvenir T-shirts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/lifestyleMolt/idUSS2714387420080427 |work=Reuters |title=Philippines' dancing jail; everyone wants to go inside |date=2008-04-27 |last=Whiteside |first=Darren}}</ref> Nineteen-year-old Egan Torrecampo, a lead dancer, said, \"When we are dancing we tend to forget why we were here in the first place.\"<ref name=\"torrecampo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jnmOPkssELU5zowV_IzW07yJEjhw |agency=AFP |last=Morella |first=Cecil |title=Jailhouse rocks for Philippine Internet dance sensations |date=2010-03-15}}</ref>\n\nTen hours after [[Michael Jackson]] died on June 25, 2009, the 1,500 CPDRC inmates performed a tribute show which included songs \"Ben\", \"I'll Be There\", and \"We Are the World\".<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OK25cfzdTTg |title=Dancing Inmate's Michael Jackson tribute |author=byronfgarcia |date=2009-06-27|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nThe \"[[Queen (band)|Queen]] Medley\" consisting of eight Queen songs notably includes the performance of popular gay/transvestite prisoner [[Wenjiel Resane]] dressed as a ballerina performing a major routine. Wenjiel was most famous for his performance in \"Thriller\" with prisoner Crisanto Nierre. The CPDRC 8-minute group performance of Queen songs ends with the appeal \"Peace to mankind\" and a quotation from Byron Garcia: \"If we make life like a living hell for these fallen angels, then we might just be turning out devils once they are released and re-integrated into society\".{{When|date=October 2012|reason= need news source and youtube video to confirm this }}{{tone inline|date=October 2012|reason=popular}}{{why|date=October 2012|reason=why is this considered a public performance}}\n\n\"[[Grease Lightning]]\" was performed on November 28, 2009, on the third anniversary of a shooting at CPDRC between feuding gangs. Arabo, a surviving gang leader, was given a lead dancer position. It was his last performance before he was transferred to Manila's Muntinlupa prison to continue his three consecutive life sentences (or minimum 90 years before parole) for a triple murder.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012|reason= need news source and youtube video to confirm this }}\n\n===''This Is It''===\n\"[[They Don't Care About Us]]\" with intro from \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\" was performed by the CPDRC inmates on January 19, 2010. The dance was specially [[choreography|choreographed]] for them by [[Travis Payne]], the Michael Jackson choreographer and associate director of ''[[This Is It (Michael Jackson concerts)|This Is It]]''. Through an initiative of [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spot.ph/2010/01/27/the-inside-scoop-on-the-cebu-inmates-international-michael-jackson-video/ |title=The inside scoop on the Cebu inmates' international Michael Jackson video |last=Musico |first=Jansen |date=2010-01-27 |work=SPOT.ph |accessdate=2012-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601121828/http://www.spot.ph/2010/01/27/the-inside-scoop-on-the-cebu-inmates-international-michael-jackson-video/ |archivedate=2010-06-01 }}</ref> Payne and two of the top dancers of Michael Jackson's ''This Is It'' show, [[Daniel Celebre]] and [[Dres Reid]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=Laurel |first=Rajo |url=http://blogs.stylebible.ph/rajosblog/2010/01/27/this-is-it/ |title=This is it |date=2010-01-27 |work=Rajo's Blog - StyleBible.ph |publisher=Summit Digital |accessdate=2012-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325004847/http://blogs.stylebible.ph/rajosblog/2010/01/27/this-is-it/ |archivedate=2013-03-25 }}</ref> performed with the CPDRC inmates in the Cebu prison, with all the inmate dancers wearing ''[[This Is It (Michael Jackson concerts)|This Is It]]'' tribute black T-shirts. Payne, Celebre, and Reid taught the routine to the inmates within 2 days, and all three took part with them in the public performance. The video shoot was part of the global launch of Jackson\u2019s ''This Is It'' DVD by [[Sony Pictures Worldwide]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=545246&publicationSubCategoryId=90 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120907004651/http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=545246&publicationSubCategoryId=90 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-07 |title=The Dancing Inmates of Cebu Goes Big Time |work=[[The Philippine Star]] |last=Maria |first=Dina Sta. |date=2010-01-31 |accessdate=2012-10-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe customized mix contained dance routines and sampling from Michael Jackson's \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\" in the intro, and a tribute to [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] while an audio of his speech is being played. [[Will Devaughn]], a popular Filipino model and actor took part in the routine carrying a poster of the African-American civil rights activist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pep.ph/news/24516/Will-Devaughn-on-Cebu-Dancing-Inmates |title=Will Devaughn on Cebu Dancing Inmates: \"They are now a part of history.\" |last=Salanga |first=Elyas Isabelo |date=2010-01-29 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |work=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]}}</ref> King is specifically mentioned in the song lyrics as well (\"Some things in life they just don't wanna see / But if Martin Luther was livin' / He wouldn't let this be\"). In addition to the dance video, a feature video of Payne and the MJ Dancers visit to the prison, the dance practices and visits to Cebu officials was made to document this initiative.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160307112305/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y6P9fQhtFyA ]</ref><!-- Video released documenting Travis Payne's visit -->\n\nPayne and company also danced to \"[[Thriller (song)|Thriller]]\" with the inmates. The \"[[Thriller (viral video)|Thriller]]\" viral video by the CPDRC inmates featuring Crisanto Nierre and Wenjiel Resane had catapulted the inmates to fame. \"Michael saw the Cebu dancing inmates on [[YouTube]] and enjoyed them immensely\", said his choreographer, Travis Payne. \"During rehearsals, we would watch and he would get tremendous joy\". [[Sony Pictures]]' [[Fritz Friedman]] told ''USA Today'', \"We thought it would be a great idea to pay homage to MJ on the occasion of the release of ''This Is It'' by going to Cebu and having Travis work with the dancers to create this piece which is from the film.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-01-27/entertainment/29436959_1_youtube-video-maximum-security-prison-prison-yard |title=Cebu, Philippines prison inmates learn new Michael Jackson dances from 'This Is It' in latest video |last=Smith |first=Olivia |date=2010-01-27 |work=New York Daily News}}</ref> The inmates also made special performance of their Michael Jackson tribute routine.\n\n=== Suspension of public performances ===\nIn February 2010, Cebu governor Gwen Garcia ordered that the program be put on hold, pending investigation of proper accounting practices for donations received by generous admirers of the CPDRC program. The inmates\u2019 longstanding choreographer, Gwen Lador also resigned. Byron's contract as Capitol security consultant had also not been renewed past 2010. Media reports talked about strains in relationships between Gwen Garcia and Byron Garcia, as Gwen instructed the Provincial Agriculture Office to continue with the reform and intensify the program on \"planting of crops inside the compound\" instead of dancing, expressing concerns that the dance performances were overshadowing the general rehabilitation program.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20100213-252934/Gwen-wants-donations-to-CPDRC-inmates-accounted-for |title=Gwen wants donations to CPDRC inmates accounted for |work=Cebu Daily News - Inquirer Global Nation |last=Israel |first=Dale G. |date=2010-02-13 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004233038/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20100213-252934/Gwen-wants-donations-to-CPDRC-inmates-accounted-for |archive-date=2012-10-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAfter a public outcry asking for the resumption of the dancing program for the inmates, Cebu Capitol consultant Rory Jon Sepulveda said that the rehabilitation by way of dancing at the CPDRC has continued, but the public viewing has been put on hold. \"The CPDRC is now on regular operations\u2014the dancing continues to be one of the rehabilitation activities\", said Sepulveda. Furthermore, Sepulveda said, \"Public performances will resume once the mechanism for full accountability on donations are in place\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20100223-254828/Net-users-call-Let-CPDRC-inmates-dance |title=Net users' call: Let CPDRC inmates dance |work=Cebu Daily News - Inquirer Global Nation |last=Israel |first=Dale G. |date=2010-02-23 |accessdate=2012-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327091633/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20100223-254828/Net-users-call-Let-CPDRC-inmates-dance |archive-date=2012-03-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also, as a sharp contrast from earlier days, {{as of|lc=on|March 2010}}, the dancing has become optional. About half of the prisoners said that they would not take part if the performances were not public.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20100303-256400/Cebu-inmates-can-dance-but-half-wont |title=Cebu inmates can dance but half won't |work=Cebu Daily News - Inquirer Global Nation |date=2010-03-03 |last=Israel |first=Dale G. |accessdate=2012-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609114111/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/news/view/20100303-256400/Cebu-inmates-can-dance-but-half-wont |archive-date=2012-06-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Governor sought the services of the original \"Thriller\" choreographer, Vince Rosales, to teach the dance routines inside the jail facility for the inmates.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\nOn September 29, 2012, after \"insistent demand\" from the public, and after many months of no online releases, the CPDRC dancers returned to perform \"[[Gangnam Style]]\", an international dance hit by [[South Korea]]n rapper [[Psy (rapper)|PSY]], in the rain.<ref name=\"gangnam\">{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/filipino-cpdrc-prison-dancers-go-gangnam-style-in-biggest-tribute-yet/story-e6frf7jo-1226487936034 |title=Filipino CPDRC prison dancers go Gangnam Style in biggest tribute yet |date=2012-10-04 |last=Crerar |first=Simon |agency=News Limited Network |work=[[The Herald Sun]] |accessdate=2012-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Dances and presentations ==\nThe following is a list of dance and presentation videos uploaded by Byron Garcia and others.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=\"75px\" | Date\n! width = \"120px\" | Title\n! width = \"120px\" | Artist\n! 